<ce:para>Diffusion of hydrogen in metals is a fundamental process in hydrogen storage in metal hydrides, hydrogen purification by metal membranes, and in hydrogen embrittlement. To develop suitable models for these processes, a detailed knowledge of the microscopic mechanisms of hydrogen motion in metallic systems is required. A semi-classically corrected version of harmonic transition state theory was applied in conjunction with plane wave Density Functional Theory to examine hydrogen diffusion in multiple C15 Laves phase AB2 compounds. This computational approach predicted tunneling contributions to hydrogen hopping between interstitial sites in complex metals readily using DFT computations. Comparison with experimental data showed that this theory correctly captures the characteristics of hydrogen diffusion in these materials over a wide range of temperatures. This method was well suited to application in complex alloys. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the 230th ACS National Meeting (Washington, DC 8/28/2005-9/1/2005).</ce:para>
